us tax liability when working months in europe i'm working in europe and will be paying taxes on my salary to the country that i'm working for what will my us tax liability be and how can i reduce my us taxes your us tax liability is the same as if you were working here in the us you do get a credit for the foreign income taxes paid and since european taxes are generally higher than us taxes you may not have any us tax liability remaining after the credit you claim the credit on form and attach it to your form tax return if you're only in europe for months out of the year you won't be eligible for the foreign earned income exclusion so i won't go into any detail on that get a copy of irs pub from the irs website it will tell you most of what you need to know as a us citizen or resident working outside the us Taxation in the United States United Kingdom corporation tax 401(k) Flat tax Tax Insurance FairTax Progressive tax Tax credit Credit card Tax haven Tax protester Tax avoidance/evasion Earned income tax credit Dividend Form 1040 Income tax Personal finance U.S. Internal Revenue Service National Insurance Dividend imputation Taxation in the Republic of Ireland Unemployment benefit Corporation Student loan Tax resistance Immigration to the United States Variable universal life insurance Constitution of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Offshore bank Economic Growth and Tax Relief Reconciliation Act of 2001 Social Security (United States) Article One of the United States Constitution Collateralized debt obligation Mutual fund Gross domestic product Member of the European Parliament Publicly funded medicine Minimum wage Double taxation Income trust Government debt Compensation of employees Capital gains tax Income statement Salary cap Accounting methods Conscription Measures of national income and output Wealth condensation Capitalism Democracy Al Gore presidential campaign, 2000 Inheritance tax Civil rights Graduate school Self-employment Military of Switzerla